headline: Nvidia CEO hopes to sell Blackwell in China, Netflix stock split
summary: Yahoo Finance's John Hyland tracks Friday's top moving stocks and biggest market stories in this Market Minute. Netflix (NFLX) stock is trading higher after the company announced a 10-for-1 stock split on Thursday. Nvidia (NVDA) CEO Jensen Huang said he would still like to sell Blackwell chips in China. Disney (DIS) is pulling ESPN, ABC, and other content from Alphabet's (GOOG, GOOGL) YouTube TV after the two companies failed to reach a new distribution agreement. Stay up to date on the latest market action, minute-by-minute, with Yahoo Finance's Market Minute.

headline: Samsung, Netflix, Disney: Trending stocks
summary: Nvidia's (NVDA) deal to provide chips to South Korea lifts Hyundai (005380.KS), Samsung (005930.KS) and Naver (035420.KS) stocks. Netflix (NFLX) shares are up on a 10-to-1 share split and a report that the streaming giant is considering entering a bidding war with Paramount Skydance (PSKY) for Warner Bros Discovery (WBD). Also in streaming, Disney (DIS) channels including ESPN and ABC went dark on YouTube TV (GOOG, GOOGL) as a pricing dispute between the two companies remains unresolved. And Taylor Swift's publisher Universal Music (UMG.AS) ends a copyright lawsuit and announces a new AI music platform. headline: Disney Channels Go Dark on YouTube TV
summary: A contract dispute between  Disney  and Google’s YouTube TV threatens to leave roughly 10 million households unable to watch multiple big sporting events this weekend.  YouTube TV stopped carrying ESPN, ABC and other Disney-owned networks Thursday night after the two sides failed to come to terms on a new distribution agreement.  There are several issues dividing the two companies, but the primary fight is over the fees Disney is seeking from YouTube TV to carry its channels.
